05109nam a22007935i 9780231510042DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2005    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315100427 a10.7312/knus136622doi  a(DE-B1597)459012  a(OCoLC)1013950571  a(OCoLC)979574227  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0150002bisacsh1 aKnust, Jennifer, eauthor.10aAbandoned to Lust :bSexual Slander and Ancient Christianity /cJennifer Knust. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGender, Theory, and Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Who'S on Top? Sex Talk, Power, and Resistance -- t1. Sexual Slander and Ancient Invective -- t2. Paul, the Slaves of Desire, and the Saints of God -- t3. Sexual Vice and Christian Apologia -- t4. The False Teachers of the End Time -- t5. Illicit Sex, Wicked Desire, and the Demonized Heretic -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly Christians used charges of adultery, incest, and lascivious behavior to demonize their opponents, police insiders, resist pagan rulers, and define what it meant to be a Christian. Christians frequently claimed that they, and they alone were sexually virtuous, comparing themselves to those marked as outsiders, especially non-believers and "heretics," who were said to be controlled by lust and unable to rein in their carnal desires. True or not, these charges allowed Christians to present themselves as different from and morally superior to those around them. Through careful, innovative readings, Jennifer Knust explores the writings of Paul, Justin Martyr, Irenaeus of Lyons, and other early Christian authors who argued that Christ alone made self-mastery possible. Rejection of Christ led to both immoral sexual behavior and, ultimately, alienation and punishment from God. Knust considers how Christian writers participated in a long tradition of rhetorical invective, a rhetoric that was often employed to defend status and difference. Christians borrowed, deployed, and reconfigured classical rhetorical techniques, turning them against their rulers to undercut their moral and political authority. Knust also examines the use of accusations of licentiousness in conflicts between rival groups of Christians. Portraying rival sects as depraved allowed accusers to claim their own group as representative of "true Christianity." Knust's book also reveals the ways in which sexual slurs and their use in early Christian writings reflected cultural and gendered assumptions about what constituted purity, morality, and truth. In doing so, Abandoned to Lust highlights the complex interrelationships between sex, gender, and sexuality within the classical, biblical, and early-Christian traditions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aLibel and slanderxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aLibel and slanderzRome. 0aSexxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory of doctrinesyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aSexzRome. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/knus13662423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231510042.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-06